lens of genre.Filmic narratives of crime open a porous space of public discourse in which filmmakers and audiences project and reimagine relations of power. Transnational Crime Cinema studies the production and reception of films from Europe, Africa, East and South Asia, and South America present crime as a discursive site where the terms of the nation and cinema gain new definition.Considered transnationally, crime cinema is a self-reflexive modality through which cinema reflects upon cinema’s own discursivity while audiences negotiate ideologies and imaginaries of nation against disruptive transnational economic and political pressures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aCrime in motion pictures. 0aMotion pictures and transnationalism. 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / Guides & Reviews.2bisacsh1 aAlpert, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerns, Fernando Gabriel Pagnoni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelahousse, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelahousse, Sarah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGashi, Jonida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKhanjani, Ramin Sadegh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartínez, David Rodríguez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOdabasi, Eren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRaj, Sony Jalarajan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRisner, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRyan, Connor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSedzielarz, Aleksander, econtribut